- content_for :title, "Grammar of the Novegradian Language — #{@current_page[:title]}"
- content_for :section_subtitle, "Синтаксе прилежимих со придѣйѕам"

= section "Types of Adjectives" do
  %p Adjectives are any words that directly modify a noun and decline in agreement with it in gender, number, and case. This includes qualitative adjectives (describing a comparable quality—1), relative adjectives (describing non-comparable qualities—2), ordinals (describing location in a sequence—3), possessives (indicating possession, much like the genitive—4), and participles (adjectivalized verbs—5).
  = example_sentence "Стари будови Новеграда стали вокражени на вуисами неборѣзам соврѣменна града.",
                     "Stári budóvi Novegráda stáli vokráźeni na vuísami neborězám sovrě́menna gráda.",
                     "old-{nom.pl} building-{nom.pl} Novegrad-{gen} become-{past}-{pl} surround.{pf}-{pass.pf.ptcp}-{nom.pl} on high-{datins.pl} skyscraper-{datins.pl} modern-{gen.sg.masc} city-{gen.sg}",
                     "The old(1) buildings of Novegrad have become surrounded(5) by the tall(1) skyscrapers of the modern(1) city."
  = example_sentence "Ярославовей Дуре на правѣ берегѣ рѣгѣ Вољхове буиле мѣстом, куде стояле срѣдновѣгеве палаце.",
                     "Iaroslávovei Dúre na právě béregě rěgě́ Vołhóve buíle mě́stom, kudé stoiále srědnověgéve paláce.",
                     "Yaroslav-{adj}-{nom.sg.masc} Courtyard-{nom.sg} on right-{loc.sg.masc} shore-{loc.sg} river-{gen.sg} Vołhóve-{nom} be-{past}-{masc} place-{datins.sg}, where stand-{past}-{masc} medieval-{nom.sg.masc} palace-{nom.sg}",
                     "The Yaroslav(4) Court on the right(2) bank of the Vołhóve River was the site of a medieval(2) palace."
  = example_sentence "Класи концаци во другаю со дўѣдешитем.",
                     "Klási kóncaci vo drugáiu so dwědéśitem.",
                     "class-{nom.sg} finish-{3pl}-{mid} second-{acc.sg.fem.def} with twenty-{datins}",
                     "Classes end at 2:20.",
                     :comment => "(lit. “second(3) [hour] with twenty [minutes]”)"

= section "Agreement" do
  = section "Across a Copula" do
    %p Across a copula, adjectives must still agree in gender, number, and case with their subject. Unlike nouns, an adjective functioning as the complement does not take the dative/instrumental case.
    = example_sentence "Мой лубиме куѣте: шинье.",
                       "Mói lubíme kuě́te: śínje.",
                       "my-{nom.sg.masc} favorite-{nom.sg.masc} color-{nom.sg} Ø blue-{nom.sg.masc}",
                       "My favorite color is blue."
    = example_sentence "Немноге ших нигоу – велем староу.",
                       "Nemnóge śíh nigóu – vélem stárou.",
                       "few this-{part.pl} book-{part.pl} Ø very old-{part.pl}",
                       "Some of these books are very old."
    %p Any subjects modified by a numeral other than one take nominative plural agreement across a copula. This is because the adjective is modifying the numeral, strictly speaking, as the noun is subordinate to the numeral. The numeral “one”, едене, on the other hand is a true adjective, subordinate to the noun it modifies.
    = example_sentence "Дова стоғана пивок – суѣши еден.",
                       "Dóva stoğána pivók – suě́śi iéden.",
                       "two-{masc} glass-{gen.sg} beer-{part.sg} Ø better-{nom.pl} one-{acc.sg.masc}",
                       "Two glasses of beer are better than one."

  = section "With Dual Nouns" do
    %p Dual nouns and pronouns always take plural agreement from adjectives (with the exception of the dative/instrumental dual, as described in #{link_to "Section 12.8", novegradian_grammar_page_path(:nounsyntax, anchor: 's12-8'), class: 'xref'}).
    = example_sentence "О ме треба нов очок.",
                       "O mé tréba nóv očók.",
                       "at I.{lat} need-{nom.sg} new-{gen.pl} glasses-{gen.pl}",
                       "I need new glasses."

  = section "With Pluralia Tantum" do
    %p All pluralia tantum nouns naturally take plural agreement. This includes those that are semantically singular, such as #{t "крѣуностия", "krěunostijá"} “fortress”. However, since these nouns are semantically singular, they can take adjectives that plural nouns generally cannot, including the numeral #{t "едене", "iédene"} “one”. This leads to somewhat unusual sights as #{t "едни крѣуностия", "iédni krěunostijá"} “one fortress”, with a morphologically plural adjective “one”.

  = section "With Compound Nominal Phrases" do
    %p Novegradian forms compound nominal phrases such as “apples and oranges”, where two different nouns together play a single semantic role such as the subject or direct object, using the preposition #{t "со", "so"} “with”, which requires the dative/instrumental case. This means that a compound subject will therefore consist of two nouns—one nominative and one dative/instrumental. This complicates adjective agreement significantly.
    %p When both nouns are singular:
    %ul
      %li
        If an adjective modifies only one noun, or two different adjectives modify the two nouns, each agrees with the noun it is modifying:
        %br
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("слазко яблоко со вокусном оранжем", "slázko iábloko so vókusnom oránźem", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “a sweet apple and a tasty orange”
      %li
        If an adjective modifies both nouns, it appears in the same case as the first noun, but plural, though is put after the second noun:
        %br
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("яблоко с оранжем вокусни", "iábloko s oránźem vókusni", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “a sweet apple and orange”
    %p When both nouns are dual or plural:
    %ul
      %li
        If an adjective modifies only one noun, or two different adjectives modify the two nouns, each agrees with the noun it is modifying:
        %br
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("слазки яблога со вокуснами оранжам", "slázki iablogá so vókusnami oranźám", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “sweet apples and tasty oranges”
      %li
        If an adjective modifies both nouns, there are multiple options. Either a single plural adjective agreeing with the first noun is placed either before the first noun or after the second, or a plural definite adjective agreeing with the first noun is placed after the second noun. All of these cases can be ambiguous at times, so context is important to determine the intended meaning:
        %br
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("слазки яблога с оранжам", "slázki iablogá s oranźám", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “sweet apples and oranges”
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("яблога с оранжам слазки", "iablogá s oranźám slázki", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “sweet apples and oranges”
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("яблога с оранжам слазкие", "iablogá s oranźám slázkije", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “sweet apples and oranges”
    %p When one noun is singular and the other plural:
    %ul
      %li
        If an adjective modifies only one noun, or two different adjectives modify the two nouns, each agrees with the noun it is modifying:
        %br
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("слазки яблога со вокусном оранжем", "slázki iablogá so vókusnom oránźem", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “sweet apples and a tasty orange”
      %li
        If an adjective modifies both nouns, then a plural adjective agreeing in case with the first noun must be placed either before the first noun or after the second:
        %br
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("слазки яблога с оранжем", "slázki iáblogá s oránźem", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “sweet apples and a [sweet] orange”
        %span.blockinlist
          = t("яблога с оранжем слазки", "iablogá s oránźem slázki", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “sweet apples and a [sweet] orange”
    %p The rules differ slightly when dealing with a participle that is subordinating a clause to a compound nominal phrase. In such circumstances, the participle agrees in case, gender, and number with the first noun, but also must be definite.
    = example_sentence "Яс нашле яблоко с оранжем, стауленое на стуљ.",
                       "Iás naślé iábloko s oránźem, staulénoie ná stuł.",
                       "I.{nom} find.{pf}-{past}-{masc} apple-{acc.sg} with orange-{datins.sg}, place.{pf}-{pass.pf.ptcp}-{acc.sg.neut.def} on table-{loc.sg}",
                       "I found an apple and orange placed on the table."

= section "Degrees of Adjectives" do
  = section "Comparative" do
    %p Comparative adjectives are used to compare two nouns in terms of a given qualitative adjective. Once the comparative suffix is added, agreement must still be made with the noun being directly modified using the comparative series of adjective endings. Infinitive verbs may also be used in place of nouns, but with neuter agreement.
    = example_sentence "Ша егра – интереснейша.",
                       "Śá iegrá – interesnéiśa.",
                       "this-{nom.sg.fem} game-{nom.sg} Ø interesting-{comp}-{nom.sg.fem}",
                       "This game is more interesting."
    %p A comparison to another noun is accomplished with #{t "неже", "néźe"} “than” followed by the accusative case, which often shortens to #{t "неж", "neź"}. A comma must immediately precede неж(е). If the things being compared are two nouns, неж(е) be dropped completely, and no comma is needed.
    = example_sentence "Ша суде егра – интереснейша(, неж) шу тамо егру.",
                       "Śá sudé iegrá – interesnéiśa(,neź) śú támo iegrú.",
                       "this-{nom.sg.fem} here game-{nom.sg} Ø interesting-{comp}-{nom.sg.fem} (, than) this-{acc.sg.fem} there game-{acc.sg}",
                       "This game is more interesting than that game."
    = example_sentence "Вожити маленей возе-те леже, неж валий.",
                       "Vóźiti málenei vóze-te léźe, neź válij.",
                       "drive-{inf} small-{nom.sg.masc.def} car-{nom.sg}-{top} Ø easy-{comp}-{nom.sg.neut}, than Ø large-{acc.sg.masc.def}",
                       "Driving a small car is easier than driving a large one.",
                       :comment => "(неж cannot be dropped here because two verbs are being compared)"
    %p The comparative adjectives #{t "болше", "bólśe"} “bigger” and #{t "менише", "méniśe"} “smaller” can also be used quantitatively, where they mean “more” and “fewer” respectively. These comparative adjectives must be in their definite forms.
    = example_sentence "Суде болшие дешити воз.",
                       "Sudé bólśije déśiti vóz.",
                       "here Ø big-{comp}-{nom.pl.def} ten-{acc} car-{gen.pl}",
                       "There are more than ten cars here."
    %p The definite form must be used in the example above because the noun вози “cars” is being dropped to avoid a redundant-sounding phrase. If fully expanded, the above sentence is equivalent to Суде есат болши вози, неже дешити воз, literally “Here there are more cars than ten cars”.
    %p The preposition #{t "на", "na"} and the accusative case are used to qualify the difference between the two things being compared.
    = example_sentence "Она кракьа мене на шеньи сентиметер.",
                       "Oná krákja mené na śénji sentiméter.",
                       "she.{nom} small-{comp}-{nom.sg.fem} I.{acc} on seven-{acc} centimeter-{gen.pl}",
                       "She’s shorter than me by seven centimeters."
    %p A comparison of equality (“as... as”) is made using #{t "тако (же)... како", "tako (źe)... kako"}. Note the use of the nominative case after како in the example below, as this could be considered a clipped form of “He as is smart as Einstein [is]”.
    = example_sentence "Оне тако же онме, како ’Ейнштейне.",
                       "Óne táko źe ómne, kako Einśtéine.",
                       "he.{nom} thus {emph} intelligent-{nom.sg.masc}, as Einstein-{nom}",
                       "He’s as smart as Einstein."
    %p The invariable forms #{t "векье неж", "vékje neź"} “more than” and #{t "менише неж", "méniśe neź"} “less than” are used to compare finite verbal phrases. One of the verbs may be dropped if they are the same and have the same subject.
    = example_sentence "Яс лублун цервено вино векье неж (лублун) бѣлое.",
                       "Iás lublún cérveno vinó vékje neź (lublún) bě́loie.",
                       "I.{nom} love-{1sg} red-{acc.sg.neut} wine-{acc.sg} more than (love-{1sg}) white-{acc.sg.neut.def}",
                       "I like red wine more than (I like) white wine."
    %p Векье is also used to form comparatives out of participles, which generally are incapable of taking regular comparative endings. It may be found in the Novegradian equivalent of the “more of an X than a Y” construction as well, which may be more accurately translated as “it is not a Y, so much as [it is] an X”.
    = example_sentence "Ше нет отуѣта, тѣм векье неж пуитем.",
                       "Śe nét otuě́ta, tě́m vékje neź puítem.",
                       "this-{nom.sg.neut} be.{3sg.neg} answer-{gen.sg}, that.{datins.sg} more than question-{datins.sg}",
                       "This is more of a question than an answer."
    %p The adverb #{t "егье", "iegjé"}, when put before a comparative adjective, means “even [more]” and strengthens it further: #{t "егье болше", "iegjé bólśe"} “even bigger”.

  = section "Superlative" do
    %p Superlative adjectives mark the greatest degree of some quality. For the most part, they share their forms with the comparative and rely on context to distinguish the two. In 17 below, for example, only the superlative makes sense; “the bigger mountain in the world” is nonsensical.
    = example_sentence "’Евересте – вуихьей горой во вием мирѣ.",
                       "Everéste – vuíhjei góroi vo vijém mírě.",
                       "Everest-{nom} Ø high-{comp}-{datins.sg.fem} mountain-{datins.sg} in all.{loc.sg.masc} world-{loc.sg}",
                       "Mt Everest is the highest mountain in the world."
    %p If confusion might arise, the prefix #{t "най-", "nai-"} added to the comparative form forces it to be interpreted as a superlative. This should not be used unless absolutely necessary, as its overuse sounds very uneducated.
    = example_sentence "Новеграде-те градем со многе „firsts‟. Буиле о тово пирве кремене на вией Ружи, старши властерни драги на срѣдновѣгевѣ Еуропѣ, и една зе найранеш систем градоун канаљ, знацин вие то-це буиле едене зе найцишекь град Еуропѣ при шем епохѣ.",
                       "Novegráde-te grádem so mnóge “firsts”. Buíle o tovó pírve krémene na vijéi Ruźí, stárśi vlásterni drági na srědnověgévě Ieurópě, i iédna ze nairáneś sistém gradóun kanáł, znacín vijé tó-ce buíle iédеne ze naicíśekj grad Ieurópě pri śém iépohě.",
                       "Novegrad-{nom}-{top} Ø city-{datins.sg} with many.{datins} “firsts”. Be-{past}-{masc} at {top.gen.sg} first-{nom.sg.masc} kremlin-{nom.sg} on all.{loc.sg.fem} Rus’-{loc}, old-{comp}-{nom.pl} paved-{nom.pl} road-{nom.pl} on medieval-{loc.sg.fem} Europe-{loc}, and one-{nom.sg.fem} from {super}-early-{comp}-{gen.pl} system-{gen.pl} urban-{gen.pl} channel-{gen.pl}, mean-{adv.impf} all.{nom.pl} {rel.acc.sg}-that.{nom} be-{past}-{masc} one-{nom.sg.masc} from {super}-clean-{comp}-{gen.pl} city-{gen.pl} Europe-{loc} during this-{loc.sg.masc} epoch-{loc.sg}",
                       "Novegráde is a city of many firsts—it had the first kremlin in all of Rus’, the oldest paved roads in Medieval Europe, and one of the earliest city sewers, making it one of the cleanest cities in Europe at the time."
    %p Expressions such as “second-largest”, “third-largest”, etc (combinations of comparative and ordinals) are formed periphrastically using the explicit superlative forms. The expression “second-largest X” is literally rendered as “second from the largest X”. This is one situation where the най- prefix is required.
    = example_sentence "Неуграде – друге зе найболеш град Республикѣ.",
                       "Néugrade – drúge ze naibóleś grád Respúblikě.",
                       "Néugrade-{nom} Ø second-{nom.sg.masc} from {super}-large-{comp}-{gen.pl} city-{gen.pl} Republic-{gen.sg}",
                       "Néugrade is the second largest city of the Republic."

  = section "Intensive" do
    %p The intensive prefix #{t "прѣ-", "prě-"} is more or less equivalent in meaning with the adverb #{t "велем", "vélem"} “very”. While it can be used with any comparable adjective, many speakers hesitate with applying it to recent loans.
    = example_sentence "Она мнѣ содагла прѣинтересну нигу.",
                       "Oná mně́ sodaglá prějinterésnu nígu.",
                       "she.{nom} I.{datins} give.{pf}-{past}-{fem} {intens}-interesting-{acc.sg.fem} book-{acc.sg}",
                       "She gave me a very interesting book."
    %p It is also commonly used in certain fixed descriptions of historical and religious figures: #{t "Мария Прѣцистая", "Maríja Prěcístaia"} “the Most-Pure Virgin Mary”, #{t "Ярослау Прѣмудрей", "Iarosláu Prěmúdrei"} “Yaroslav the Wise”.
    %p After #{t "каде", "kadé"} “what a...”, the prefix is very frequently used for emphasis. Here it would generally not be translated.
    = example_sentence "Каде прѣкрасне ше дене!",
                       "Kadé prěkrásne śé déne!",
                       "what_kind-{nom.sg.masc} {intens}-beautiful-{nom.sg.masc} this-{nom.sg.masc} day-{nom.sg} Ø",
                       "What a beautiful day!"
    %p The intensive prefix is most commonly used attributively. When the intensified adjective appears in the predicate, then the adverb #{t "велем", "vélem"} is usually preferred.

  = section "Excessive" do
    %p The stressed prefix #{t "во-", "vó-"} indicates excessiveness, much like the English adverb “too (much)”. It is equivalent to and may be accompanied by the adverb #{t "намног", "namnóg"} “by far”, which generally follows the adjective it modifies. Excessive-degree adjectives may either directly modify a noun or employ copulas.
    = example_sentence "Ша драга – водиляна!",
                       "Śá drága – vódiliana!",
                       "this-{nom.sg.fem} road-{nom.sg} Ø {excess}-long-{nom.sg.fem}",
                       "This road is too long!"
    = example_sentence "Оне мене направиле по драгѣ водилянѣ намног!",
                       "Óne mené naprávile po drágě vódilianě namnóg!",
                       "he.{nom} I.{acc} direct.{pf}-{past}-{masc} along road-{loc.sg} {excess}-long-{loc.sg.fem} by_far",
                       "He led me down too long of a road!"
    %p If some modifying clause is subordinated to an excessive-degree adjective, the adverb намног must appear as well.
    = example_sentence "Ша ленина-та вовала намног со тѣм-це одѣвалеш би яс тѣм.",
                       "Śá lénina-ta vóvala namnóg so tě́m-ce oděváleś bi iás tě́m.",
                       "this-{nom.sg.fem} shirt-{nom.sg}-{top} {excess}-big-{nom.sg.fem} by_far with {rel.acc.sg}-that.{nom} dress-{past}-{masc}-{mid} {subj.sg} I.{nom} {top.datins.sg}",
                       "This shirt is too big for me to wear."
    %p Not all adjectives beginning with a stressed во- are excessive. Some are just coincidence, such as #{t "вокусне", "vókusne"} “tasty”.
    %p “Too many/much” and “too few/little” are expressed using the adverbs #{t "вомноге", "vómnoge"} (or #{t "вомноже", "vómnoźe"}) and #{t "вомало", "vómalo"} (or #{t "вомале", "vómale"}), respectively, with the following noun in the partitive case.

  = section "Trial Superlative" do
    %p The trial superlative #{t "тре-", "tre-"} is no longer productive in its original function as a superlative. The most common domain where it is found remains in religious terminology.
    %p However, in common usage it has gained a new function as a marker of sarcasm or hyperbole, a usage perhaps comparable to “scare quotes” in English. This is a colloquial phenomenon and should never appear in more formal contexts.
    = example_sentence "Тако-и, оне рѣѕиле то-це егзамене-те тревайкей ест.",
                       "Táko-i, óne rědzíle tó-ce iegzámene-te treváikei iést.",
                       "thus-be.{3sg.clitic}, he.{nom} say-{past}-{masc} {rel.acc.sg}-that.{nom} exam-{nom.sg}-{top} {tri}-difficult-{nom.sg.masc.def} be.{3sg}",
                       "Yeah, he said the test was ‘really difficult’."
    = example_sentence "Трекласная Катя натлеклаш со дуерюм.",
                       "Treklásnaia Kátia natlekláś so dueriúm.",
                       "{tri}-classy-{nom.sg.fem.def} Kátia-{nom} collide.{pf}-{past}-{fem}-{mid} with door-{datins.sg}",
                       "Oh-so-smooth Kátia walked into a door."

= section "Definite Adjectives" do
  %p Definite adjectives have three functions: nominalization, marking specifity, and topicalization agreement. This last usage is discussed later.

  = section "Definite Adjectives Marking Nominalization" do
    %p When not modifying nouns directly, definite adjectives by themselves often indicate the ellipsis of the noun being modified, often “person” or “people”: #{t "оѕание [луди]", "odzánije [lúdi]"} “learned [people]” (by extention, “scientists”), #{t "ванная [комната]", "vánnaia [kómnata]"} “bath [room]” (“bathroom”), #{t "русская [жена]", "rússkaia [źená]"} “Russian [woman]”, etc. Each of the above can act as full nouns, albeit with adjectival declension; the full forms including the dropped noun are rarely seen except for emphasis.
    %p This is particularly common with dropped topics. This usage is considered different than that described above because it is context-dependent. The meaning of ванная will be understood the same way in any situation, while добрей “good” would not.
    = example_sentence "„Котрий кажик-от тортек хокьеш?‟ „Содай мнѣ болшей.‟",
                       "“Kótrij kaźik-ót torték hókjeś?” “Sodái mně́ bólśei.”",
                       "“which-{acc.sg.masc} piece-{dimin}-{acc.sg}-{top} cake-{part.sg} want-{2sg}?” “give.{pf}-{2sg.imper} I.{datins} big.{comp}-{nom.sg.masc}",
                       "Which piece of cake do you want?” “Give me the bigger [one]."
    %p In general, a lone definite adjective not modifying any noun can be interpreted as “the X one”, unless it is a set expression such as ванная.

  = section "Definite Adjectives Marking Specificity" do
    %p One of the most common uses for the definite adjectives is marking the specificity of a noun. Specificity, a distinction made in Novegradian that tends to give non-natives quite a bit of trouble, is similar to definiteness in that it singles out a single noun from all others. However, unlike definiteness, it tends to specify more of a “the one and only” sort of quality, meaning specificity is more or less independent of context, while definiteness is strongly linked to it. This distinction may best be explained through examples.
    %p The phrase #{t "“Новеградеска(я) граница”", "Novegrádeska(ia) graníca"} means “Novegradian border”. The definite form, Новеградеская граница, refers to the entire borders of the Republic of Novegrad. A question such as “Where is the Novegradian-#{abbrev 'def'} border?” would be used, for example, to ask someone to identify the nation’s border on a map. The indefinite form, Новеградеска граница, refers to “any” Novegradian border, or more properly, any sections of it. A question such as “Where is the Novegradian-#{abbrev 'indef'} border?” would be used in asking someone for directions to the border. Notice how specificity is independent of definiteness—the “indefinite” (or perhaps more accurately, “non-specific”) phrase новеградеска граница is translated as “the Novegradian border”. Using the wrong specificity in a certain context will frequently cause unexpected results. If someone wanted directions but asks for the location of the (definite) Novegradian border, the reply will be something along the lines of “It starts at the Arctic Ocean, runs along Sweden into the Baltic Sea...” (or perhaps more likely a strange look from someone wondering why anyone would pull over to ask such a strange question).
    %p Another example is the phrase #{t "“Новеградеске(й) универсидате”", "Novegrádeske(i) universidáte"}, “Novegradian university”. The definite/specific form Новеградескей универсидате refers to Novegrad State University (in full Новеградескей Сударестуенней Универсидате), located in Novegráde Velíkei. The indefinite/non-specific form новеградеске универсидате refers to any university in Novegrad, or to an ethnically Novegradian university. Again, these terms are independent of definiteness in the English sense. A question such as Куде новеградеске универсидате? by itself would be translated as “Where is a Novegradian university?”, but in the context of a conversation about a Novegradian university and a Finnish university, it would be translated as “Where is the Novegradian university (as opposed to the Finnish)?” The specific form “Куде Новеградескей Универсидате?” will always result in the reply “In Novegráde Velíkei”.
    %p Any adjective, not just national ones, can display specificity: Цервеней дуре <i>Cérvenei dúre</i> “Red Square (Moscow)”, цервене дуре <i>cérvene dúre</i> “a red square or plaza”.
    %p Definite adjectives, as shown in several of the above examples, often form part of place names or specific locations, such as “Novegrad University” and “Red Square”. The tendency to use definite adjectives with place names is so strong that they will be used even when an indefinite meaning is impossible, such as #{t "Варижеское море", "Variźeskóie móre"} “the Baltic Sea”. Even though there are no other ‘baltic seas’ in existance, the Baltic Sea must take the definite form.
    %p Adjectives modifying nouns that already have definite adjectives must also be definite:
    = example_sentence "Старовѣгевей Ярославовей Дуре сохудит со заложеньа Велигаево Новеграда.",
                       "Starověgévei Iaroslávovei Dúre sohúdit so zaloźénja Veligáievo Novegráda.",
                       "medieval-{nom.sg.masc.def} Yaroslav-{adj}-{nom.sg.masc.def} courtyard-{nom.sg} come_from-{3sg} from foundation-{gen.sg} Great-{gen.sg.masc.def} Novegrad-{gen}",
                       "The ancient Yaroslav Court dates to the foundation of Novegráde Velíkei."
    %p However, when a definite adjective modifies a noun phrase already including an adjective, there can be specificity disagreement.
    %p In the example below, the definite adjective is modifying the phrase водне панти “waterway”, not just панти “way, route”, which allows there to be specificity disagreement. However, if another adjective were added to the phrase (e.g., “long”), it would have to be definite because it would now be modifying the entire phrase Вољго-Варижескей водне панти, which is definite.
    = example_sentence "Вољго-Варижескей водне панти розрѣжаст то-це вѣни музут преплавит вмести мора Цернаево со Каспийскием и мора Варижескаево.",
                       "Vółgo-Varíźeskei vódne pánti rozrěźást tó-ce vě́ni múzut preplávit vmésti móra Cernáievo so Kaspíjskijem i móra Variźeskáievo.",
                       "Volga-Baltic-{nom.sg.masc.def} water-{adj}-{nom.sg.masc} way allow-{3sg} {rel.acc.sg}-that.{nom} ship-{nom.pl} be_able-{3pl} sail_between-{sup} between sea-{gen.sg} Black-{gen.sg.neut.def} with Caspian-{datins.sg.neut.def} and sea-{gen.sg} Baltic-{gen.sg.neut.def}",
                       "The Volga-Baltic waterway allows ships to sail between the Black and Caspian Seas and the Baltic Sea."

= section "Possessive Adjectives" do
  %p Common Slavic frequently formed possessive constructions by converting the possessor into an adjective. This process is no longer productive in Novegradian, but it has left behind many traces.
  %p There were two main classes of possessive adjectives. In earlier forms of Novegradian (and still in the northern dialects of the language), the first was formed by adding the suffixes #{t "-ине", "-ine"} to first, second, and sixth declension stems, #{t "-ове", "-ove"} to third declension stems, and #{t "-еве", "-eve"} to fourth and fifth declension stems, identical in origin to the derivational suffixes that are still used today. These would decline as regular adjectives#{footnote}. These are the original source of many surnames ending in <i>-ou</i> or <i>-ine</i>, but which now decline as regular nouns.
  %p On the other hand, many names of towns and other locations in Novegrad end in #{t "-ово", "-ovo"} or #{t "-ино", "-ino"}, the neuter form of the original adjectives. Such place names generally do still decline as neuter adjectives, though this does vary; some towns advocate adjectival declension while others advocate nominal declension.
  %p Other instances of originally possessive adjectives have since adopted new meanings: #{t "братеве", "bráteve"} “fraternal” (originally, “brother’s”), #{t "материне", "máterine"} “maternal”, etc.
  %p The other form of possessive adjective was formed with the suffix *-j-, which frequently resulted in consonant mutations. These types of possessives have almost all adopted a new fixed meaning and are no longer viewed as possessives; the suffix itself ceased to be productive no later than the 14th century. However, many animal names have both a regularly-derived adjective form and a possessive form, such as #{t "кошене", "kóśene"} “feline” versus #{t "кошие", "kóśie"} “cat’s”. Both forms are now identical in meaning and are fully interchangeable. However, certain disciplines may prefer one or the other form; zoological and taxonomical fields prefer the -j- forms whenever available, for example.
  %p Only two truly possessive adjectives remain in common usage in the standard language, #{t "Боже", "Bóźe"} “God’s” and #{t "Христове", "Hristóve"} “Christ’s”, both of which were preserved due to Church Slavonic influence. While they do not have to, they typically follow the possessed noun. In the written language they should always be capitalized.
  = example_sentence "Она кѣловала игону-то с образем Христовом.",
                     "Oná kělovála igónu-to s óbrazem Hristóvom.",
                     "she.{nom} kiss-{past}-{fem} ikon-{acc.sg}-{top} with image-{datins.sg} Christ-{poss}-{datins.sg.masc}",
                     "She kissed an ikon with the image of Christ."
  %p While the genitive #{t "Христа", "Hristá"} could be substituted and the sentence would remain grammatical, most speakers find would find it rather awkward to do so.

= section "Adjective Modifiers" do
  %p There are a number of common adverbs and expressions used to modify the intensity of adjectives. Some of these include:
  %ul
    %li #{t "велем", "vélem"} — “very”
    %li #{t "воплонѣ", "vóploně"} — “quite, to a great degree”. Not as strong as велем.
    %li #{t "во добрѣ степеньи", "vo dóbrě stepenjí"}, #{t "домѣрнѣ", "doměrně"}, #{t "намѣрнѣ", "naměrně"}, #{t "мѣрнѣ", "měrně"} — “fairly, rather”. Not as strong as воплонѣ. The first three have positive connotations, while мѣрне has more of a negative connotation. Во добрѣ степеньи is somewhat bookish and more typical of higher registers, though its more colloquial varient #{t "во степеньи", "vo stepenjí"} is more common in speech, but unacceptable in writing. Намѣрнѣ is limited to more casual registers.
    %li #{t "також", "tákoź"} — “so”. This form must be placed before the adjective being modified. Alternatively, #{t "тако", "táko"} may be placed before the adjective and #{t "же", "źe"} after it: #{t "також интересне", "tákoź interésne"}, #{t "тако интересне же", "táko interésne źe"} “so interesting”.
    %li #{t "вѣрнѣ", "věrně"}, #{t "попраудой", "popráudoi"} — “really”. An intensive like велем, but also attempts to counter perceived disbelief on the part of the listener/reader.
    %li #{t "велнѣ", "vélně"}, #{t "достоенѣ", "dostóieně"} — “enough”. Велнѣ is generally only used to modify adjectives modifying people, while достоенѣ can modify any adjective. The former must go before the adjective, while the latter can go either before or after. Достоенѣ also has the colloquial variant #{t "достай", "dóstai"}.
    %li #{t "маленѣ", "máleně"} — “a little bit”. Must go before the adjective.
    %li #{t "маломаленѣ", "malomáleně"} — “a tiny bit”. Must go before the adjective.
  %p All of the above modifiers may be placed either before or after the adjective unless otherwise specified.
  %p There are also a number of comparative modifiers. Note that not all of them require the comparative form of an adjective, even though they have a comparative meaning:
  %ul
    %li #{abbrev 'comp'} + #{t "намног", "namnóg"} “much more” — #{t "мокнейше намног", "moknéiśe namnóg"} “much more capable”
    %li #{t "егье", "iegjé"} + #{abbrev 'comp'} — “even more”: #{t "егье мокнейше", "iegjé moknéiśe"} “even more capable”
    %li #{t "менишѣ", "méniśě"} + #{abbrev 'adj'} — “less”: #{t "менишѣ мокне", "méniśě mókne"} “less capable”
    %li #{t "менишѣ", "méniśě"} + #{abbrev 'adj'} + #{t "намног", "namnóg"} — “much less”: #{t "менишѣ мокне намног", "méniśě mókne namnóg"} “much less capable”
    %li #{t "егье менишѣ", "iegjé méniśě"} + #{abbrev 'adj'} — “even less”: #{t "егье менишѣ мокне", "iegjé méniśě mókne"} “even less capable”
    %li #{t "немногом", "nemnógom"} + #{abbrev 'comp'} — “a bit more”: #{t "немногом мокнейше", "nemnógom moknéiśe"} “a bit more capable”
    %li #{t "немногом менишѣ", "nemnógom méniśě"} + #{abbrev 'adj'} — “a bit less”: #{t "немногом менишѣ мокне", "nemnógom méniśě mókne"} “a bit less capable”
  %p The adverb #{t "немногом", "nemnógom"} may freely be replaced by its diminutive #{t "немножком", "nemnóźkom"}.

= section "Secondary Predicate Adjectives" do
  = section "True Predicates" do
    %p Secondary predicate adjectives are adjectives that describe the subject or object of the sentence during the performance of the verb (e.g., “Ieváne came home drunk”), as opposed to an intrinsic quality of the subject (“Drunk Ieváne came home”) or an adverb modifying the verb (“Ieváne drunkenly came home”). In Novegradian, secondary predicate adjectives appear after the primary predicate; they agree with their head in gender and number, but are always in the dative/instrumental case and indefinite, no matter the case and definiteness of the head noun. When there is both a subject and direct object present in the sentence, it can be ambiguous which the adjective is modifying unless their genders are distinct.
    = example_sentence "Оне пришле думове пяном.",
                       "Óne priślé dumóve piánom.",
                       "he.{nom} arrive.{pf}-{past}-{masc} homeward drunk-{datins.sg.masc}",
                       "He came home drunk."
    = example_sentence "Яс ѣ овидѣле плацакьой.",
                       "Iás iě́ ovíděle placákjoi.",
                       "I.{nom} she.{acc} see.{pf}-{past}-{masc} cry-{act.impf.ptcp}-{datins.sg.fem}",
                       "I saw her crying."

  = section "Other Adjectival Adjuncts" do
    %p Transitive verbs that can nevertheless take an adjectival argument also make it dative/instrumental and indefinite, agreeing in gender and number with whatever their logical head may be.
    = example_sentence "Яс соцедовам ѣ красной.",
                       "Iás socédovam iě́ krásnoi.",
                       "I.{nom} consider-{1sg} she.{acc} beautiful-{datins.sg.fem}",
                       "I consider her beautiful."
    %p Verbs that normally can take a predicate adjective in the nominative case instead use the dative/instrumental when the subject is eliminated. This can be seen, for example, in the adjectival and adverbial participles of буити “be” or стати “become”, which can take complements directly but not subjects. However, even when the adverbial participles are used as simultative verbs, the complement must remain in the dative/instrumental.
    = example_sentence "Буиве застауленом вноу и вноу, о ни треба рѣжатиш отружити ли престауленье.",
                       "Buíve zastáulenom vnóu i vnóu, o ní tréba rěźátiś otruźíti li prestaulénje.",
                       "be-{adv.pf} delay-{pass.pf.ptcp}-{datins.sg.masc} again and again, at we.{lat} need-{nom.sg} decide-{inf}-{mid} cancel.{pf}-{inf} whether performance-{nom.sg}",
                       "Having been delayed time after time, we need to decide whether to cancel the performance."
    %p This is also true of complements of буити or стати when the verb is impersonal. The adjective will always be neuter in such cases.
    = example_sentence "Добро ест буити младом.",
                       "Dóbro iést buíti mládom.",
                       "good-{nom.sg.neut} be.{3sg} be-{inf} young-{nom.sg.masc}",
                       "It’s good to be young."

  = section "Semi-Predicatives" do
    %p The three adjectives #{t "едене", "iédene"} “alone”, #{t "саме", "sáme"} “by oneself”, and #{t "раде", "ráde"} (no English equivalent, see below) are known as semi-predicatives, since they act more like adverbs yet show case agreement. They may pattern either as regular adverbs or as secondary predicates, but generally appear in the nominative case, not the dative/instrumental.
    = example_sentence "Она ошла една.",
                       "Oná oślá iédna.",
                       "she.{nom} leave.{pf}-{past}-{fem} one-{nom.sg.fem}",
                       "She left alone/by herself."
    = example_sentence "Ше-то саме музун дѣлати!",
                       "Śé-to sáme múzun dě́lati!",
                       "this-{nom.sg}-{top} by_oneself-{nom.sg.masc} be_able-{1sg} do-{inf}",
                       "I can do it myself!"
    %p Sentences with #{t "раде", "ráde"} are often translated into English using verbs such as “like” or “enjoy”. It lacks an English adverbial equivalent, except in the future tense where it is similar to “gladly” or “with pleasure”. It is frequently interchangeable with the verb #{t "радети", "radéti"} “enjoy”, except that раде cannot be negated to mean “do not enjoy”.
    = example_sentence "Яс раде говорун сон ей.",
                       "Iás ráde govorún son iéi.",
                       "I.{nom} gladly-{nom.sg.masc} talk-{1sg} with-{n*} she.{datins}",
                       "I enjoy talking with her."
    = example_sentence "Яс раде прийдун ко ваме во наступну снѣжену.",
                       "Iás ráde prijdún ko váme vo nastúpnu sně́źenu.",
                       "I.{nom} gladly-{nom.sg.masc} arrive.{pf}-{1sg} towards you.{datins.pl} in next-{acc.sg.fem} December-{acc.sg}",
                       "I will gladly visit you next December."
    = example_sentence "Они ради не работати.",
                       "Oní rádi ne rabótati.",
                       "they.{nom} gladly-{nom.pl} {neg} work-{3pl}",
                       "They enjoy not working."
    %p In impersonal sentences or in other situations where there is no true subject, the three semi-predicatives take a special ending: #{t "едну", "iédnu"}, #{t "саму", "sámu"}, #{t "раду", "rádu"}. This fossilized form originates from an old dative case ending that Novegradian has long since lost in other words, and is known as the “impersonal dative”.
    = example_sentence "Мнѣ тривожно буити едну.",
                       "Mně́ trivóźno buíti iédnu.",
                       "I.{datins} disquieting-{nom.sg.neut} be-{inf} one-{dat.impers}",
                       "Being alone makes me feel uneasy."
    = example_sentence "Раду танцасци!",
                       "Rádu tancásci!",
                       "gladly-{dat.impers} dance-{3sg}-{mid}",
                       "Dancing is fun!"

= section "Numbers" do
  = section "Inanimate Numerals" do
    %p In Novegradian, case is generally marked on the numeral while the noun is forced to agree with the numeral modifying it.
    %p Едене (1) is a pronominal adjective, and declines in the same way as other pronouns such as ше “this”. It always appears in the same case and number as the noun it modifies.
    = example_sentence "Една глава – добро, а довѣ – суѣше.",
                       "Iédna gláva – dóbro, a dóvě – suě́śe.",
                       "one-{nom.sg.fem} head-{nom.sg} Ø good-{nom.sg.neut}, whereas two.{fem}-{nom} Ø better-{nom.sg.neut}",
                       "One head is good, but two is better."
    %p Other numbers observe a direct/indirect case distinction, with different behaviors depending on whether the noun phrase bears a direct case (nominative or accusative) or an indirect case (all others). In the direct cases, the numeral assumes the nominative or accusative case, and then assigns a particular form to the noun, often identical to the genitive case. In indirect cases, both the numeral and noun assume the same case, more akin to a typical adjectival relationship.
    %p The numerals дова/довѣ (2), три/трѣ (3), and цетири (4) all typically force the noun they modify to take the special count form in direct cases. This form is identical to or close to the genitive singular for masculine and neuter nouns, and the nominative plural for feminine nouns; the exact formation rules are described in the relevant nominal and adjectival morphology sections. In indirect cases, the noun takes the same case as the numeral, and is plural.
    %p However, for the handful of nouns with a distinct dual form, the rules for дова/довѣ (2) are slightly different. In this case, the quantified noun always takes the same case as the numeral in its dual forms.
