        %td
          = t("соправа", "sopráva", :linebreak => true)
          %br
          “from the right”
    %p All of the locative adverbs also have more colloquial forms with initial stress and a zero-ending locative: #{t "воврех", "vóvreh"} “above”, #{t "вониз", "vóniz"} “below”, #{t "наврех", "návreh"} “upstairs”, #{t "наниз", "nániz"} “downstairs”, #{t "вопред", "vópred"} “ahead”, #{t "позад", "pózad"} “behind”, #{t "налѣу", "nálěu"} “on the left”, #{t "напрау", "náprau"} “on the right”. In speech, these are far more common than the full forms listed in the table.
    %p There is no distinction between “from above/below” and “from upstairs/downstairs”.
    = example_sentence "Койда доѣдеш до прешѣка, повради шебе колѣвом.",
                       "Kóida doiě́deś do préśěka, povradí śebé kolě́vom.",
                       "when go_up_to_by_vehicle.{pf}-{2sg} up_to intersection-{gen.sg}, turn.{pf}-{2sg.imper} {reflx.acc} leftward",
                       "When you reach the intersection, turn left."

  = section "Велем ‘Very’" do
    %p The adverb #{t "велем", "vélem"} “very” may modify verbs as well as adjectives, unlike in English.
    = example_sentence "Велем хокьун ѣхат Суайѕарюн.",
                       "Vélem hókjun iě́hat Suaidzáriun.",
                       "very want-{1sg} go_by_vehicle.{det}-{sup} Switzerland-{lat}",
                       "I really want to visit Switzerland."

  = section "Думове ‘Homewards’" do
    %p The semi-nominal adverb #{t "думове", "dumóve"} means “homewards”, originating from an old dative case form of дум “house” that is no longer used in Novegradian#{footnote}. It can be used with any verb indicating movement toward.
    = example_sentence "Оне хокьет ис думове.",
                       "Óne hókjet ís dumóve.",
                       "he.{nom} want-{3sg} go.{det}-{sup} homeward",
                       "He wants to go home."
    = example_sentence "Яс пришле думове.",
                       "Iás priślé domóve.",
                       "I.{nom} arrive.{pf}-{past}-{masc} homeward",
                       "I arrived at home."
    %p Whose home may be specified using the preposition #{t "о", "o"} plus the genitive case.
    = example_sentence "Идун думове о Надалин.",
                       "Idún dumóve o Nadálin.",
                       "go.{det}-{1sg} homeward at Nadália-{gen}",
                       "I’m going to Nadália’s house."
    %p With pronouns, however, the situation is more complex. The same о + genitive construction may be used for the first and second persons, but in the third person, the bare genitive is used. This is usually considered a relic of the adverb’s original nominal origin.
    = example_sentence "Идун думове ѣ.",
                       "Idún dumóve iě́.",
                       "go.{det}-{1sg} homeward she.{gen}",
                       "I’m going to her house."

  = section "Стреми ‘-First’" do
    %p The adverb #{t "стреми", "strémi"} is also a quasi-nominal in that it can take nominal arguments. It does not have a direct English analogue, but is much like the morpheme ‘-first’ in expressions like “headfirst”. It takes nominal complements in the dative/instrumental case.
    = example_sentence "Оне понурале стреми главой.",
                       "Óne ponurále strémi glávoi.",
                       "he.{nom} dive.{pf}-{past}-{masc} first head-{datins.sg}",
                       "He dove headfirst into the water."
    %p It is also used idiomatically in a number of ways that it cannot be in English.
    = example_sentence "Оне вехода худит стреми омем.",
                       "Óne vehodá húdit strémi ómem.",
                       "he.{nom} always go.{indet}-{3sg} first mind-{datins.sg}",
                       "He always keeps a level head."
    %p In addition to conveying a sense of “preceding”, стреми (which originally meant something along the lines of “steep[ly]”) can also imply something is beneath something else. Compare the two senses in the following sentences.
    = example_sentence "Она лежила нав озянѣ стреми ногам.",
                       "Oná leźíla nav oziáně strémi nogám.",
                       "she.{nom} lie-{past}-{fem} on-{v*} bed-{loc.sg} first leg-{datins.pl}",
                       "She lay backwards on her bed.",
                       :comment => "(i.e., her head towards the foot of the bed)"
    = example_sentence "Она лежила нав озянѣ стреми желудокем.",
                       "Oná leźíla nav oziáně strémi źeludókem.",
                       "she.{nom} lie-{past}-{fem} on-{v*} bed-{loc.sg} first stomach-{datins.sg}",
                       "She lay on her stomach on her bed."

  = section "Bare Adverbs" do
    %p Bare adverbs and impersonal adjectives used as interjections must take the topical ending #{t "-то", "-to"}. This only applies to adverbs that are phonologically a single word (that is, having a single stress), which does not necessarily correspond to one written word.
    = example_sentence "Во концѣ-то!",
                       "Vo kóncě-to!",
                       "in end-{loc.sg}-{top}",
                       "Finally!"
    = example_sentence "Яро-то!",
                       "Iáro-to!",
                       "fierce-{nom.sg.neut}-{top}",
                       "Cool!"
    %p This persists so long as the adverb is being used as an interjection, even if there is a sentence providing context.
    = example_sentence "Во концѣ-то ти пришле!",
                       "Vo kóncě-to tí priślé!",
                       "in end-{loc.sg}-{top} you.{nom} arrive.{pf}-{past}-{masc}",
                       "Finally you showed up!"
    %p However, if the bare adverb is being used interrogatively, the то is replaced by #{t "ли", "li"}. This is written as a separate word.
    = example_sentence "Оне пришле во концѣ ли?",
                       "Óne priślé vo kóncě li?",
                       "he.{nom} arrive.{pf}-{past}-{masc} in end-{loc.sg} {q}?",
                       "He finally showed up?"

%section.footnotes
  = footnote do
    In Old Novegradian, these possessive adjectives were always indefinite. However, as they began to lose their productivity, their declension was brought more in line with other adjectives, and since most surviving possessive adjectives were found in place names, they naturally became definite. Modern Novegradian dialects that still have productive possessive adjectives vary in their usage; some maintain the older pattern of always declining as indefinite adjectives, while others may freely switch between definite and indefinite just as any other adjective would.

  = footnote do
    This ending is typically considered to be a case of “ending spreading” rather than a true dual adjective declension, where the dual ending -ама spreads from the noun to the adjective, replacing the very similar adjectival plural -ами. However, it is never used when the noun lacks a distinct dual (and there is therefore nowhere for the ending to “spread” from).

  = footnote do
    In the National Corpus, the prevalence breakdown is roughly as follows:
    %ul
      %li 2-4 with count form: 75%
      %li 2-4 with nom/acc pl: 25%
      %li 5-10 with nom/acc pl: 90%
      %li 5-10 with gen pl: 10%

  = footnote do
    It is actually the same ending that the fourth declension dative/instrumental ending for humans, #{t "-ой", "-oi"}, is derived from, although думове underwent a different phonetic development due to its reanalysis as an adverb. The form #{t "думой", "dumói"} is seen in some dialects as well, but is nonstandard.
